    "Let me analyze the mapped transformation to identify the reaction center.\n\nLooking at the reaction SMIRKS:\n\nReactants: [H:20][OH:21].C1=C(C=C(C(=C1Br)O)Br)C[N:10]2C(N=C3C(=C2N)NC(=O)N3C4C(C(C(O4)CO)O)O)[O-].[Br-]\n\nProducts: [H:20][N+:10]1(C(N=C2C(=C1N)NC(=O)N2C3C(C(C(O3)CO)O)O)[O-])CC4=CC(=C(C(=C4)Br)O)Br.[OH-:21].[Br-]\n\nKey mapped atoms:\n- [H:20] and [OH:21] are separate in reactants (water: H-OH)\n- [N:10] is the nitrogen in the reactant\n\nIn reactants:\n- [H:20] is bonded to [OH:21] (this is water: H-OH)\n- [N:10] is a tertiary amine nitrogen (connected to the aromatic ring and the heterocyclic ring)\n\nIn products:\n- [H:20] is bonded to [N+:10] (now N+ with H attached)\n- [OH:21] is now [OH-:21] (hydroxide ion)\n- [N:10] becomes [N+:10] (quaternary ammonium)\n\nSo the reaction center is:\n- The N:10 atom changes from tertiary amine to quaternary ammonium (gains a positive charge and a hydrogen)\n- The O:21-H:20 bond breaks (water dissociates)\n- A new N:10-H:20 bond forms\n- O:21 gains a negative charge (becomes OH-)\n\nThis is essentially a protonation of the amine nitrogen by water, where water donates a proton to the nitrogen, leaving hydroxide as the counterion.\n\nThe reaction center involves:\n1. Bond break: O:21-H:20\n2. Bond formation: N:10-H:20\n3. Charge change: N:10 goes from neutral to +1 (quaternary ammonium)\n4. Charge change: O:21 goes from neutral to -1 (hydroxide)\n\nSo the reaction center is: O:21-H:20 bond breaks, N:10-H:20 bond forms; N:10 gains positive charge, O:21 gains negative charge.\n\nLet me format this as a reaction edit summary:\n\nBond break: O:21-H:20\nBond form: N:10-H:20\nCharge change: N:10 (0 → +1), O:21 (0 → -1)"
